According to the method for assessing risk of extinction for plants of the Mexican norm (MER-Plantas; SEMARNAT 2010 ), this species qualifies as “Endangered” since it attained a score>2 (2.04), with each of the four criteria rated as follows (maximum value for each = 1): A (characteristics of its geographical distribution) = 1; B (characteristics of its habitat) = 0.78; C (intrinsic vulnerability) = 0.26; and D (impact from human activities) = 0.0. Moreover, this species also qualified as Endangered by two “shortcut” MER-Plantas criteria: (I) Its known area of distribution in Mexico is under 1 km 2 and (II) the number of individuals recorded is less than 500. Likewise, according to the IUCN Red List criteria ( IUCN 2012 ), at the regional level it qualifies as Endangered by Criterion D (population size estimated to number less than 250 mature individuals). Formal assessments of its risk status in the Bahamas and the Greater Antilles are lacking due to the paucity of information on its distribution, abundance and potential threats (
Ackerman et al. 2014
).
